node.text:
Wherever in the world that you find yourself, color is there — light is there. In our Discover Your Yellow series with @Expedia, we invited you along on a journey fueled by curiosity, creativity, and courage. These elements are essential to our travels, and allow us to connect with the places we go in a deeper, more impassioned way. Whether it’s watching the sunrise from a mountaintop or sharing a laugh with friends on the road, travelers are experts at following the rhythms in life that give us strength. From Japan to Hawaii, Arizona to Barcelona, we heard four inspiring individuals share their stories with us.
__
Are you the writer, photographer, designer, or dreamer? What are you seeking to discover? Where will you find it? Watch them all, let us know, and remember — you’re always writing your story. #ExpediaYellow #PassionPassport

node.text:
From reaching hidden waterfalls by kayak to snorkeling along the island’s shorelines, our partners at @Expedia invited us along on a trip to Kauai, Hawaii, last year, with speaker and author @RuthieLindsey to explore her close relationship with the natural world on a deeper level through an array of new experiences. As a young woman, chronic pain slowly pulled Ruthie away from everything she once held dear: her faith, her family, her body, and her very self. After not being able to travel during seven bed-ridden years, she now embraces every circumstance for what it is with grace and determination to find healing in ways that inspire her.
__
Head to the link in our bio to see how the color yellow seemed to greet her at every step of the way, reminding her to treasure every circumstance in life for what it is—a lesson learned over the years of her life that led to these moments.
__
What does the color yellow mean to you? Let us know in the comments! 💛 #passionpassport #ExpediaYellow

node.title: Expedia Yellow: Discovering Healing in Kauai with Ruthie Lindsey

node.text:
From the bold colors of the autumn season to the intense colors of temples and shrines, in this episode of “Expedia Yellow: Discover Your Adventure” with @Expedia, we set out to Japan with Photographer @MichaelGeorge last year to explore his close relationship with the magical color. For Michael, growing up in Florida, yellow was the sun. Always present, year-round, beating down on you relentlessly—it gave everything light and also seemed to slowly burn the world away. Today, it means something more to him.
__
Head to the link in our bio to read more about how the color yellow has sparked his creativity and his burning desire to continue creating in our one-on-one interview. #ExpediaYellow #ExpediaPic #PassionPassport

node.title: Expedia Yellow: Discovering Adventure in Japan with Michael George

node.text:
Designer and photographer Demas Rusli (@demas) was once skeptical about solo travel. Living in Australia and working in an architecture firm, his enthusiasm and curiosity about use of color and space were his main sources of inspiration. He didn’t want to travel just to visit a place, or boast about his destination. Last year, when our partners at @Expedia planned his trip to Barcelona, he discovered that there was another option: inhabiting the places we travel, and having them inhabit us. Even though he went solo, the warm and playful character of Barcelona both intrigued his eye for design and made him feel at home. All in all, it just inspired to keep Demas doing what he was doing, and stay on track — a message we could all use in this moment.
__
In this episode of “Expedia Yellow: Discovering Creativity,” we follow Demas on his solo-trip through Barcelona and learn how the architecture, light, and design helped him discover his creativity.
__
Head to the link in our bio to read more about how the color yellow inspires him to create in our one-on-one interview with Demas. 💛
#ExpediaYellow #Passionpassport

node.title: Expedia Yellow: Discovering Creativity in Barcelona with Demas Rusli

Last year, we rode along with art director Anne McIsaac (@yellowillow) and @Expedia on a road trip through Arizona that inspired us to think about how travelers learn to take life at their own pace — and maintain that pace even in unforeseen circumstances. Chasing the color yellow across the otherworldly western landscapes, Anne’s journey took her on hot air balloon rides and dreamy drives to catch the next sunset or streak of light on the red rocks of the desert. In this episode of “Expedia Yellow: Discovering Courage,” we follow Anne’s footsteps as she traces the story of her journey with Parkinson’s and her very close creative relationship with the color yellow.
__
Head to the link in our bio to read more about Anne and how the color yellow reminds her to seek joy and curiosity at all times. What does the color yellow mean to you? Let us know in the comments! 💛 #ExpediaYellow #PassionPassport

node.title: Expedia Yellow: Discovering Courage in Arizona with Anne McIsaac

node.text:
Welcome to another episode of our “Passport to the 🌎” IGTV Series! This week, @seanslobodan takes us to Utah’s Zion National Park through a trailer for his upcoming feature film, “Where Forever Is Now,” a dedication to its beautiful and powerful land.
__
"The country's national parks might be closed right now, but work goes on behind the scenes to preserve their spirit of adventure and prepare them for the next generation of visitors. Whether you are creative who gains inspiration from the natural world or collaboration with others, Utah's Zion National Park is still synonymous with adventure, even at a time when our experiences are so limited. I hope that our new film encourages people to go out and find their own stories, whether you're streaming it from home or watching in the park's museum auditorium. There's a lifetime of things to see in Zion, but this is a reminder to value the quality of experience over quantity. Like any healthy relationship, we have to be willing to give back to nature as much as we take. It starts with a little less self-interest and a little more self-awareness."
__
A version of this film entitled "We The Keepers" will play every 30 minutes at Zion for the next 10-15 years, with a feature-length cut to be released later this year at festivals. Director Sean Slobodan, @seanslobodan, of @lcl.studio says it's what we do now that will determine what the future looks like in places like our National Parks, and that to stream the video to the public during the closures is a way to emphasize that each of us has an impact. "I firmly believe that the only way we're going to create change in the way that we impact our public lands is by connecting with them personally." 🎥@seanslobodan and @lcl.studio #passionpassportvideo #passionpassport
__
To watch “We The Keepers,” head over to Sean’s Instagram for the link to the full video!

node.title: Passport to the 🌎 : Zion National Park

Welcome to another episode from our "Passport to the 🌎" IGTV series! This week, filmmaker @bryanhynes_ takes us on a heartfelt journey to Tanzania.
__
"I had the pleasure of leading an expedition team of international high school students from Dubai. We traveled through Tanzania over a two-week trip, where we trekked through the Southern Parre mountains and local villages. We also worked with a local Massai community in Arusha to help build a beautiful empowerment center for women. A visit to the famous Ngorongoro Crater for a safari tour provided us with the opportunity to witness a variety of incredible wildlife. Throughout this experience, I felt a sense of connection to our world and the human spirit. In many ways, the culture shock of living in rural villages with basic resources was both eyeopening and humbling. It allowed me and my team to reflect on what is important in our lives and to appreciate the little things. I also realized that, as humans, we're not so different. No matter where you come from, we all share in commonalities and can celebrate what makes us unique."
__

We're back with another edition of our "Passport to the 🌎" IGTV series! This time around, our friend @matiasderada takes us to the breathtaking Salt Flats of Bolivia.
__
"In February of this year, I had the opportunity to revisit the Salt Flats of Bolivia. It had been four years since my last visit, but the memory of its never-ending reflection left a lasting impression. It's always been my dream to witness sunset or sunrise in this place, so this time around, I decided to camp for two days with my good friends @theboliviantraveler, @jimenasuarezv, and @arturoplataa. The footage that you see in this video encapsulates my two-day experience, which I can only describe as being both awake and dreaming at the same time. With that feeling in mind, it was only fitting to pair it with a song that feels as if someone is talking to you in your sleep and guiding you through this moment. As cheesy as it may sound, this place is magical in every aspect, and I would come back here a million times if I could."
__

From reaching hidden waterfalls by kayak to snorkeling along the island’s shorelines, our partners at @Expedia invited us along on a trip to Kauai, Hawaii with speaker and author @RuthieLindsey to explore her close relationship with the natural world on a deeper level through an array of new experiences. As a young woman, chronic pain slowly pulled Ruthie away from everything she once held dear: her faith, her family, her body, and her very self. After not being able to travel during seven bed-ridden years, she now embraces every circumstance for what it is with grace and determination to find healing in ways that inspire her.

Head to the link in our bio to see how the color yellow seemed to greet her at every step of the way, reminding her to treasure every circumstance in life for what it is, a lesson learned over the years of her life that led to these moments.

What does the color yellow mean to you? Let us know in the comments! 💛 #passionpassport #ExpediaYellow #ExpediaPic

node.title: Discover Your Yellow: Episode 1—Kauai, Hawaii | Expedia

For Sean Slobodan, a Utah-based director and founder of Local. Studio, the outdoors has always inspired and driven him to create immersive videos that transport his viewers. This film showcases all the beauty that the majestic state of California has to offer. It was a passion project with no clients dictating the schedule or vision: “The state is so big and different from top to bottom that I liked the idea of putting something together that went way beyond the Hollywood experience that most people think of. The film was shot throughout three separate trips and took a total of 3-4 weeks of shooting. This project, in particular, provided a kind of freedom in a film that I don’t often get to feel and experience. We had made some plans before each leg of the trip, but overall we just shot what we saw and luckily a lot of it turned out.” Want to see more videos from @lcl.studio, Sean's Utah-based production company? Check out their website and read our article to learn more about their shooting experience across California. Filmmaker Brent Foster has made it a goal to say "yes" to every place he's invited to see, so when he had the chance to explore Rajasthan for a few days after wrapping a commercial shoot, he jumped at it:

Having spent about a year and a half in India, I knew to expect sensory overload. India is the type of place that you need to embrace and accept for what it is. It’s a visual artist’s paradise, but also a great test on any traveler. It’s one of those places where you have to recognize that you have no control over what goes on around you.

This personal project was the result of this exploration and is a reminder of why I got into filmmaking in the first place — to explore. It was so rejuvenating to step away from the constraints I often feel when doing commissioned work and to just open myself up to being there with the camera with no preconceived shots or expectations.

I find that passion projects, regardless of what stage you're at as a filmmaker, are key to keeping you inspired and loving what you do. I hope to always have one on the go and can't recommend it enough to other filmmakers and travelers. I want to challenge people making their first travel video to get out of their comfort zone and get as close to people as you can when filming. It’s easy to sit back with a zoom lens and capture life from afar. Try to immerse yourself in the process, and you may be surprised by the results.

Want to see more of Brent's films? Visit our website to read our interview with him. For more films from around the world, follow our new IGTV series, “Passport to the 🌎." 🎥: @brentfoster 📍India 🇮🇳#passionpassportvideo #passionpassport

I exited the plane at Kotoka airport nervous and apprehensive, it had been 12 long years since I was last in Ghana. At that time, I was a kid who unfortunately didn't appreciate the things the country had to offer. In the 12 years since that visit, I have traveled to other continents, yet never felt much desire to visit home. A mindset all too common among the African Diaspora. But as I waited in line at customs, dancing to the live music that was playing all I could think was, what took me so long?

Africa is never portrayed as a travel destination for creatives. So as someone who experiences travel through the lens of my camera, I worried I'd find very little to shoot. The day I discovered Jamestown, one of Accra's oldest districts, it was eye-opening. As I got to know Jamestown's people and history, I found myself shooting almost non-stop. Trying to capture all the rich moments and personal stories I was experiencing.

During my trip, I also had the chance to connect with members of Ghana's vibrant creative scene. People such as Prince Jyesi (@princejyesi) & Kuukua (@kuuksss), who are doing amazing things, and are creatives determined to disrupt the stereotypical narrative surrounding Africa.

Despite having had a lot of fun rediscovering the art, food, and colors of Accra. The absolute highlight of my trip was visiting a school my dad and uncle have built. Although I had been hearing about it for years, this was my first time seeing the school for myself. It was incredible! Which is why the school and its students are the first things you see in the video.

Want to see more of Prince's travel videos? Visit his profile and check out his IGTV. For more films from around the world, follow our new IGTV series, “Passport to the 🌎" 🎥: @principality 📍Ghana 🇬🇭 #passionpassportvideo #passionpassport

node.text:
📷 @emmaexpedition 📍Bryce Canyon National Park, Utah, USA 🇺🇸 "The southwest of the United States is where I call home, so I'm always looking to explore unique places in the desert with every chance I get. As a result, Bryce Canyon National Park happens to be one of my favorite parks in the region, and I always make a point to visit whenever I'm nearby.

I remember prepping for this trip as I watched an interview with a big-time landscape photographer. He mentioned that one of his favorite photography exercises was taking a 70-200mm lens to Bryce Canyon, spending hours finding interesting compositions in the landscape, and photographing them. With that idea fresh in my mind, that's what I intended to do as well. After a few hikes in and out of the canyon, I slowed down to take the time to find those unique compositions when I finally landed this shot.

Interestingly enough, I ended up taking this shot with a 7-year-old 24-70mm F/2.8 lens that had stopped auto-focusing and was in rough shape. And yet, even with those challenges, I embraced the equipment I had at my disposal to create this photo. Truthfully, I would have never thought about taking this photo if it wasn't for the small setbacks I had to work through with that lens.

Technicals aside, if you ever find yourself at Bryce Canyon, be sure to never miss a sunrise — it's the most magical time of the day there when the morning sunlight makes the canyon glow and is best experienced in person.

And lastly, one of the most important things you can do before visiting is learning about the history of the land. Bryce Canyon is on Southern Paiute, Fremont, Hopi, Zuni, Ute, Navajo, and Anasazi Ancestral land. Learning about this history will make you feel more connected, and I have found that I am more creative when I take the time to learn about these beautiful places." #passionpassport

node.text:
📷 @Waqonthewildside 📍White Sands National Park, New Mexico, USA 🇺🇸 "I’m not sure what cast a spell on me first — the state’s tagline, ‘Land Of Enchantment,' or seeing photos of Santa Fe’s Pueblo-Moorish architecture, learning about the establishment of the country's oldest Islamic community in Abiquiu, New Mexico, or the beautiful white sands that can be seen for miles — either way, I knew I had to see them all with my own two eyes.

The road trip from Florida had many stops, some spanning several days, but the destination was always New Mexico, and the final stop, the crown jewel, White Sands National Park.

If you’re like me, you’ve seen numerous pictures from this park and have fantasized about visiting, but nothing prepares you for the sheer magnificence of these White Sands. Even the 8-mi Dune Drive upon entering the park does not get you ready for the incredible beauty of the largest gypsum dune field on the planet. Only after parking, and a short hike, when you come upon scenes like this do you finally realize you might as well be on another planet.

Layers upon layers of white sand dunes, with silhouettes of humans traversing through them like ants, the sweet smell of sand verbena filling the air, the setting sun casting patterns on distant mountains, and lighting up the sky with all shades of orange truly make it an enchanting experience." #passionpassport

With this newfound occupational freedom, you’ve probably already asked Google how to become a digital nomad. 🎥 @vuhai.ng 📍Italy 🇮🇹 "It was a few months ago when the pandemic was still striking Italy, and we were not allowed to go outside of our region, which is Lombardia for me. As a result, I wanted to go somewhere that was less popular and not easily accessible, so I could travel and remain socially distanced from crowds. Before taking this video, I had to walk around for quite a while just to find the best angle. After seven months of not touching my drone, the experience of using it once again, which is one of my favorite things to do, was most meaningful.

After this experience, I realized that while traveling around the world is fun and exciting, staying local is equally great, especially in Italy, where beauty is bountiful. Moving forward,  I'm committed to spending more time showcasing Italy's charm, and Lombardia in particular, even more.

And just because travel maybe a little more difficult now, that doesn't mean our passion for it has to stop. Do your best to support local and travel local, and stay safe!"
__

📷@etchd 📍Greenland 🇬🇱 "In 2019, I had the incredible opportunity to explore and capture marketing content in Svalbard and Eastern Greenland on assignment for Aurora Expeditions.

Anyone who has ventured to Eastern Greenland knows that it truly is an enormous and remote part of the world. It's a stark difference to its east-facing lands, with only one main settlement along the entire Western coastline. Accessing these locations isn't possible without a ship, making this part of the world highly inaccessible to most.

Throughout the entire trip, I was in awe of the weird and beautiful landscapes that we encountered with each kilometer traveled. And with 24-hours of great light, it was nearly impossible for any photographer to go to sleep at night — in case we missed opportunities like this.

Cruising past the rich red cliffs of Nanortalik was like looking back through time. The compacted rock and earth displayed millions of years of the planet's history, made even more picturesque by the floating icebergs that had become trapped along the coastline."
__

node.text:
Fairytale-like landscapes, alpine scenery, snow-capped mountains, glittering lakes, and bucolic beauty galore, Switzerland is a paradise quite like none other.  This is one of the reasons why this landlocked nation is a popular destination for tourists from all over. While its hamlets and picture-perfect villages are a highlight, the cities of Switzerland are equally attractive too.  With alluring sights, medieval streetscapes, cobbled pathways, and intriguing old towns, many of these cities are also significant global financial and banking centers. A country for all seasons, there is plenty to see and do in Switzerland beyond its pastoral charm.⁠
⁠
Interested in learning more? Head to the link in our bio for a closer look at five eclectic cities to explore on your next visit to Switzerland. 📷 @cemerk85 📍Zurich, Switzerland 🇨🇭 #passionpassport

node.text:
📷@storiesmatter 📍Lalibela, Ethiopia 🇪🇹 "Fasika (Easter in Amharic). is the most important festival for the Ethiopian Orthodox Church. It was an honor for me to witness a Good Friday service in Lalibela in preparation for breaking their 55-day fast on Resurrection Sunday.

Just before the sun sets, pilgrims dressed in all white fill the rock-hewn churches, praying, reflecting, remembering, and listening to the priests. At one point, they start to circle around the church, carrying wooden crosses, surrounded by the smell of incense and accompanied by the sound of drums and chants, symbolizing the route that Jesus Christ took to his crucifixion.

At the end of the ceremony, the people receive a blessing from the priests and long green grass from the churches’ holy pools, representing the crown of thorns put on the head of Jesus on Good Friday — with some tying it around their head to wear. During this time, the most devout pilgrims have their ’Last Supper' on Thursday evening and do not eat or drink anything until Sunday morning.

This is a sacred day of slowing down that holds space for pain, discomfort, and grief, preparing everyone’s hearts for what is to come. Spending time in the tension of what was known and what was not yet realized. The space between."
__

node.text:
📷@bonvoyagecleo 📍Venice, Italy 🇮🇹 "I had wanted to see Venice for a long time, even though I had always imagined seeing the city alone to escape the romantic and sometimes 'too cliché' side of it. Despite this, I still managed to visit with those of whom I love, pure and true — my parents. It was August of 2020, and we managed to coordinate our respective schedules. With the ongoing pandemic, there weren't many opportunities to travel, and there seemed to be fewer people than usual, so we decided to drive from our hometown, Nancy, France.

Venice is the perfect playground for photographers. We stayed one week, which gave us time to explore the city, but not all of it — still leaving some mystery to be uncovered for next time. I tried to fill my passion for solo travel with my desire to escape in all these little streets, to take pictures of every single window, completely hypnotized by the beauty of the city. 

For years, my mom has been under a curse of sorts, simply suffering from bad luck it seems. Without fail, she hurts herself before each summer. This time, she fell while visiting me at home in July. Due to her fragile bones, she was limping, and I could see her suffering from every step — but a mother's love is infinite, right? When I travel with my family, even if my father practices photography, it is mostly her who accompanies me, even when I insist on seeing the sunrise on the Serenissima.

Venice is the city of love, and therefore reminds me of the love I have for her, above all else. Today, I am still in Italy and my parents in France, and I must admit that I miss them a lot. I see these photos as a reminder of their love and everything they do for me.

This experience reminds me to enjoy being present in the moment. Even if my mom wasn't in the greatest of shape, these are still happy moments. This year will be more complicated to go on vacations together since the 'curse' continues to poke its head out each year, but I am happy to have all these beautiful memories with me anyway!"
__
Have you had the opportunity to travel with your parents before? Let us know about your experience in the comments below. #passionpassport

🎥@zimydakid 📍Costa Rica 🇨🇷 "Costa Rica has the most beautiful and healthy forests that I have ever seen, and wow, did it ever feel good to witness such beauty and biodiversity! Here, there's an inexplicable magnificence in every little detail of nature that is unparalleled anywhere else. On this day, it was a rainy afternoon, but, as usual, @immadiscoveler and I didn't want to take a day off to rest, so we went out to explore what we could. As a result, we found ourselves in this incredible location with the best atmosphere that we could have hoped for."
__
Are you one to let the rain ruin your plans? Or are you getting out and exploring, no matter what? Let us know in the comments below. #passionpassport

📖: 6 Epic Things to Do in Lassen Volcanic National Park
📝 & 📷: Jessica Wright (@bontraveler)
__
With a diverse landscape, Lassen Volcanic National Park is a destination you can’t miss while visiting Northern California. This national park truly has it all, even four types of volcanoes. You’ll find crystal-clear lakes, boiling mud pots, epic hiking trails, and a lot of wildlife. 

“After visiting for my first time this last year on an outdoor socially-distanced weekend, I found myself eager to return again. The sheer beauty and untouched aspect to this park took me by surprise.”
__ To read more from Jessica’s experience in Lassen Volcanic National Park and get some of her tips to help plan your trip, head to the link in our bio. #passionpassport

🎥 @nicoleo__ 📍Cinque Terre, Italy 🇮🇹 "What started as a passion for photography many years ago has evolved into a deep love for showing and sharing authentic experiences from my home country of Italy. I always try to showcase the things I love most about Italy, like the true Italian life and people, traditions, habits, and our culture. This video is a collection of clips from all over Cinque Terre (Manarola, Rio Maggiore, Vernazza, Corniglia, and Monterosso).

Thanks to a connection made from my Instagram community, I had the opportunity to experience and live in the 5 Terre in a unique and non-replicable situation during lockdown restrictions. 5 Terre, which is about 120km from my hometown of Genoa, is one of the most beautiful places on earth. Because of this, the area is always full of tourists from all around the world. During this unforgettable weekend, I tried to show the magic atmosphere of these lands, showing empty corners and short moments of life from its elderly locals — something I try to do in every town or village I visit in Italy. Among all the difficulties and problems my country has faced, I do my best to showcase its three main pillars: its enormous and unreplicated beauty, the passion and love for the 'good life,' and the simplicity of the little things." #passionpassport
__
🎶: @ludovico_einaudi

🎥@michelleospino_ 📍Grumeti Game Reserve, Tanzania 🇹🇿 "I went on my first African safari in April of this year, and I fell completely in love with the whole experience. There's no real way to describe how I felt reconnecting with nature. There's a crazy energy that comes with waking up at 5:30 am every day; seeing the most breathtaking sunrises; the sounds of the bush coming to life; the people; the insane tracking skills of the guides; their encyclopedia-like animal facts; knowledge of animal behavior; and the companionship that you build with them all.  With all these feelings running high, I had to go back, so I booked a last-minute solo trip to Kenya and Tanzania.

This video was taken shortly after we ventured out on a morning drive. Lions are most active in the early mornings, and when we stumbled upon this pride, the cubs were playing with each other around a watering hole. They moved on to this area where the grass was shorter and the morning light was glowing when I got the opportunity to make this video. The behavior of lions is fascinating to watch. Most experiences in the bush are based on being in the right place at the right time. Shortly after, the entire pride moved to the shade under a bush to rest for the day.

Living in a big city for so many years, it feels meditative to spend time in nature. It heals the soul and is something that I vow to do more of with intention. With that comes learning more about how we as humans can protect and preserve these spaces and the nearby communities." #passionpassport
